Exercise: least squares regression

Use the /states.rds/ data set. Fit a model predicting energy consumed per capita (energy) from the percentage of residents living in metropolitan areas (metro). Be sure to 1. Examine/plot the data before fitting the model 2. Print and interpret the model summary' 3.plot the model to look for deviations from modeling assumptions

Select one or more additional predictors to add to your model and repeat steps 1-3. Is this model significantly better than the model with /metro/ as the only predictor?

energy.mod1<- lm(energy ~ metro,data=na.omit(states.data))
summary(energy.mod1)

This models estimeate coefficient for metro is -1.6526 which means metro has negative correlation with energy. The Pr value of metro is 0.031 that means metro is a significant variable. The R squared is 0.09714 and the Adjusted R-squared is 0.07751.They both are not so high. We need improve this model.Lets add pop,area,density to the model.

Exercise: interactions and factors

Use the states data set.

  1. Add on to the regression equation that you created in exercise 1 by generating an interaction term and testing the interaction.

  2. Try adding region to the model. Are there significant differences across the four regions?

Make sure R knows region is categorical

str(states.data$region)
